<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/700"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_700_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=f3fec725051f36f3b998820e19bfd7fc&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="76" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/700">ECS researcher applies knowledge management to politics</a></h3><p>Dr Kieron O'Hara, Senior Research Fellow in ECS, has written a book which will be of particular interest to the UK's political parties as a general election looms on the horizon. Dr O'Hara has taken his expertise in knowledge management for organisations and looked at how it could be applied to a government, a country, or a political party. His new book, After Blair: Conservatism Beyond Thatcher, published this month by Icon Books, embarks on a quest for an ideological answer to the Conservatives’ difficulties.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/698"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_698_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=8d4c19dc4acc83b831c6f81b70a02341&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Dr Paul Lewin, Dr Paul Chappell, Dr Jane Burridge" title="Dr Paul Lewin, Dr Paul Chappell, Dr Jane Burridge (Copyright: ECS)" border="0" width="120" height="85" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/698">Research tackles sensory-motor learning in rehabilitation</a></h3><p>One of the greatest challenges facing sensory-motor learning in rehabilitation is being tackled by researchers at the School of Electronics and Computer Science working with the University's School of Health Professions and Rehabilitation Sciences. Their research, beginning next month, will be the first of its kind to develop and apply iterative learning control techniques to re-learning movement.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/697"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_697_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=6a67a0c49c7a831b69a5099fe8147877&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Professor Wendy Hall and Professor Jintong Lin" title="Professor Wendy Hall and Professor Jintong Lin (Copyright: ECS)" border="0" width="120" height="90" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/697">Professor Jintong Lin named 'Distinguished Alumnus' of ECS</a></h3><p>ECS graduate Professor Jintong Lin has been named 'Distinguished Alumnus' of the School.</p><p>Professor Wendy Hall, Head of the School of Electronics and Computer Science, presented Professor Lin with a framed certificate when she visited China to conclude a formal agreement with the Beijing University of Posts and Telecommunications (BUPT) of which Professor Lin is President. BUPT will now send up to 20 students each year on the new ECS MSc programme in Software Engineering.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/693"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_693_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=ff674684a84d06f1c7da2ec9dd94646b&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Raul Kripalani, Sarah Deane, Matt Sharifi" title="Raul Kripalani, Sarah Deane, Matt Sharifi (Copyright: Joyce Lewis)" border="0" width="120" height="84" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/693">Microsoft Gen ’05 student event tour hits Southampton</a></h3><p>Microsoft student partners, 2nd year ECS Computer Science students Sarah Deane (centre) and Matt Sharifi (right, with ECS student Raul Kripalani) are helping out today (Wednesday) at the Microsoft Gen ’05 student technology roadshow. The roadshow, which is visiting Southampton for the first time, gives students the opportunity to see a multitude of new products and technologies in action. Over 500 students have so far visited Gen '05 in the West Building of the University Students' Union. Lectures and demonstrations run throughout the day until 5 pm.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050317090021/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
